There is a lot to unpack here but let's try:

- Our team only runs a single dual miner/validator on this subnet (and we are currently 10th from the bottom). We do this so we can collect statistics and try to reverse engineer tech problems that come up on the subnet. 

- We appreciate that frequent updates can make mining on this subnet challenging. Whilst we do our best to make sure everyone has time to experiment with any changes on Testnet prior to any updates on Mainnet we can certainly aim to do a better job of being transparent to avoid any future misunderstandings. Will try to give more clarity below on some of the topics raised:

- The cool down was changed because we see higher quality results are bigger in size and take longer to validate (loading, rendering). We noticed that the validator network started glitching (this is an example of where running a validator was important - we got the feedback immediately and were able to react) and the 8 hour time range was changed to 4 hours because this helps CR3 punish weight copiers more.

- The use of sigmoid is in line with the idea that we want each miner to be in competition with every other miner, we believe this incentivizes even marginal improvements because your incentive can grow. When we had a tiered incentive structure we saw miners content to reach the top tier and then no longer innovate. There's a reason that the shape of the incentive curve is important to OTF (and to us) - it is a good way to judge competition

- Lastly, regarding increasing the registration costs during a period of frequent updates - this decision was made to do this to give existing miners an opportunity to adjust to the changes before new competitors would register. We typically prefer to do this when we believe the changes are significant and thus fair to those currently on the subnet.

We get there's frustration here including from miners who now see their returns lower due to the changes, but we also believe this is in part because this subnet is shifting. Previously the focus was on quantity over quality which lends itself to certain strategies, and miners did an excellent job, but now the focus is on maintaining a high quantity while also increasing quality. New opensource innovations like Trellis pose a challenge because they offer higher quality results but take longer to validate and require new metrics to prevent exploit. We are striving to update our subnet validation accordingly. We may not get every update correct, but we have tried to flag what we are changing and why to create a transparent, fair and competitive system. If you don't trust that or don't want to mine on this subnet that's certainly an option but our approach will remain the same. Future updates (e.g. ELO ranking) will attempt to improve quality and robustness and suggestions like the dashboard are really helpful because they flag things that we can build to push us in this direction

As part of our promise (in response to feedback from the miners) to be more transparent, we wanted to update you all about what our team is currently testing: 

We are currently evaluating/benchmarking a collection of models generated via **LGM**, **GRM** and **Trellis** against a variety of metrics including **LPIPS**, **SSIM**, **CLIP**, **VQA**, **IQA**, and **Laplacian Variance**. This involves:

- *Testing alternative CLIP-based methods for potentially better text-to-image alignment.*

- *Working on improving Prompt-IQA scoring. Prompt-IQA was originally trained on a mixed dataset with two proposed data augmentation strategies to learn diverse requirements. This enables Prompt-IQA model to effectively adapt to new requirements. The score of the Prompt-IQA depends on the input dataset consisting of “prompt” - score pairs (image, ground truth score). *

- *Updating the input datasets to force Prompt-IQA to evaluate models with exceptional visual appearance the highest and to evaluate models with all types of artefacts the lowest*.

Based on the results of these evaluations we aim to update the scoring formula.

# Technical Details on Aesthetic Metrics Update

For tech audience, sharing technical details. 

**We have researched and are developing following improvements to aesthetic model architecture and training:**

> -   Increasing margin in MarginRankingLoss.
> - Adding variance loss to reduce score variance within buckets.
> - Adding BatchNorm for better regularization.
> - Making the model deeper with activations (ReLU, Swish, etc.)
> - Experimenting with ContrastiveLoss as alternative to MarginRankingLoss.
> - Improving training data with hard negatives and triplets.
> - Moving from single value prediction to distribution over scores.

**Also, we researched second metric for quality assessment. Training was done with special focus to avoid overfitting and data leakage problems.**

**Technical Setup:**

> * CLIP image encoder (frozen) with 2 linear layers.
> * Dropouts and ReLU activations.
> * Binary Cross Entropy loss function.

**Key Insights:**

> * Resolved data leakage by separating overlapping train/validation datasets.
> * Enhanced model robustness through added regularizations: L2, L1, and increased dropout to 0.5.
> * Implemented extensive augmentations (geometric transforms, color, edge, blur effects).
> * Shifted to a score-based labeling system (label smoothening) for detailed classification, replacing L1 with Huber loss, which combines the benefits of both L1 and L2 regularization.

## Subnet 17 Reward Formula

@404-gen・17 

If you would like to  check the performance of your miner you can do so using the miner dashboard: https://dashboard.404.xyz/dashboards

In the Dashboard you will be able to see three metrics:

1️⃣ **Reward**
Reward = the product of the other 2 metrics (Score x Submitted Results). 

2️⃣ **Average Score (EMA)**
Your average score is calculated on an Exponential Moving Average (EMA). The older value has a weight of 0.95 and the newer value has a weight of 0.05.

3️⃣ **Submitted Results**
This is the number of results your miner has submitted. The number of results you can submit differ between synthetic and organic traffic.

> **Synthetic Traffic** 🤖 
> Cooldown is 300 seconds (including the 30 seconds to generate results). 
> `4 x 60 Minutes x 60 seconds = 48. `
> This is the maximum number of results you can submit in a 4 hour period with Synthetic Traffic.

> **Organic Traffic** 🍃 
> Cooldown is 120 seconds. It is served by Validator UID 49.  
> `4 x 60 minutes x 60 Seconds = 120.`
> This is the maximum number of results you can submit in a 4 hour period with Organic Traffic.

**Advice to Miners**

In order to be a top miner on the subnet you must strive to:

- Generate ALL tasks you receive.
- Increase your Quality Score.
- Generate within 30 seconds. This includes submitting results to the validator. If some Validators are slower to validate this needs to be factored into your 30 seconds.

This information is also contained in the FAQ in our Discord server which you can refer to here: https://discord.com/channels/1065924238550237194/1358808320948834315/1358808320948834315
